***(AI Edit-out draft 1)*** We don't often call it anxiety. We might call it "pressure", "stress", or "restlessness" and it might play out in a few different ways. A mind that runs every worst-case scenario before hitting the pillow at night. Snapping at your kids because your nervous system is on high alert. Getting stuck on the roundabout of "what ifs?".

## What's actually going on

Anxiety isn't weakness and it isn't a character flaw, it's an alarm system that's stuck in the on position. When functioning properly it's protective and useful. Just enough anxiety keeps us motivated to show up, prepare, and consider. If you knew there was a lion standing outside your door right this very moment you would – wisely so – refuse to leave your home. Unchecked anxiety though is an imaginary lion prowling your front yard convincing you to abandon any agenda you once had.

Usually it started doing a job for you a long time ago: staying vigilant kept something bad from happening, or at least it felt that way. The problem is the alarm never learned to shut off, and now it's running your schedule, your stomach, and half your decisions.

## How counseling helps

In our work together, we'll do two things at once. First, the practical: understanding how anxiety operates in your body and your week, and building real tools for the moments it spikes. Second, the deeper work: getting at the story underneath the vigilance — what you're bracing for, where you learned to brace, and what it would mean to trust God with outcomes you can't control.

That second part matters. "Do not be anxious" was never meant as a command to try harder. It's an invitation to put weight down on something that can actually hold it. Getting there is a process — and it's exactly the work we'll do.

## When to reach out

***(Nice job Claude)*** If the worry has started costing you sleep, patience, focus, or presence with your family — that's enough. You don't need a diagnosis or a breaking point to justify the call.
